snippet.textDisplay:
You guys are probably not going to see this but thank you I might have not known your dad but just hearing what he did for others and the fact that he was so selfless really reminded me that this world is full of good people and I will basically try my best to be even a quarter of the person your dad was. This video really helped me heal from some of the stuff that I was dealing with and showed that life is way too short to be mean or be negative to people. It showed me that no matter what I'm going through if Sean was able to help people while he was ill shows me that I can try my best to make a difference in others lives. I'm really sad that he left us but maybe he was just to good for this world.

I'm really sorry for your loss and just know that this documentary really changed my life for the better and left me in tears 🌸

snippet.textDisplay: Guys I am so so so sorry for your loss, and I don’t know what y’all s believes are but I have a story. snippet.textDisplay: Thank you for this video. I lost my dad who was my best friend about 2 years ago. It feels like last week I lost him it leaves such a hole in your heart my world was turned upside down. Cancer took him in 3 months. I had so many emotions watching him waste away I wanted to trade places with him and take all the pain for him. Things have gotten a little better but there are days where it feels like things aren’t right because he’s not here. There are things I want to share with him but I can’t. So many people feel this way at some point in our lives we all grieve. We learn what it means to grieve.

snippet.textDisplay:
Some people have never lost a relative/loved one etc, and for them I hope you never experience anything like that ever. Ive lost my father when i was incredibly young and my grandfather 5 years ago. Its the worst, most empty feeling ever. My father has never been in my life because he died so young. The loss of his life has never impacted me in the way of feeling his death, but the emptiness of his role stayed there my entire life. Always having to make the fathers day tie for my brother/grandfather etc. And that was fine honestly, like I understood that my entire life. What happened with him happened, and I was always too young to remember that feeling of grief.

But for me, my grandfather was one of my favorite people on earth. He lived in India so I couldn’t see him often, but when he came home I was always with him. He had dementia, and so he would constantly be repeating what he said etc. It drove my grandmother mad, and everyone would be annoyed but never me. I was always fine with him repeating himself, and I never minded. It was always fine, because there was just something about his gentle presence and overall kindness that always comforted those around him.

Throughout the years, his condition got worse and worse, to the point where he didn’t really understand anything, and he was almost just not there. Its like he had just checked out, and was just in pain. At this point they wouldn’t come all the way to America anymore, the trip was just tiresome for him. We’d try and talk to him over call, but my mom wouldn’t let me talk to him. I hate to say how much resentment that built up in me, I was furious. But how could I tell the woman losing her father to stop guarding me from the pain she’s going through, and let me see him like how he was. She was only trying to protect my memory of him.

And then, February 3rd, 2014, he passed away. I never got to say goodbye, I never got to see him again. He was just...gone. The funeral happened in India, and after a few days, I was back home. It didnt feel real. It was almost incredibly numbing. I didn’t feel any grief for months. Its been five years, and god i miss him a lot. It of course has been a few years so I’ve like ‘moved on’, but I really shouldn’t kid myself here because I may never really move on. Watching this documentary really brought me to an emotional state which I tend to avoid at all costs, and for that I’m really grateful.

Death and loss makes a person feel incredibly isolated, and it almost feels like no one else on earth is going through it, but you’re not alone. Anyone going through it right now, you are not alone and never will be alone. There are millions of people going through what you’re going through, always remember that. I felt alone with what I was going through, even though I knew people lose loved ones everyday. It still hurts to remember him, listen to songs that remind me of him etc, but I’ll always be grateful for him and what he’s done for our lives.
